Sunday, May 31, is the last night The Tribune's printing press will run; the newspaper will be printed at our sister paper, the Fresno Bee, beginning June 1.

Our newsroom, advertising, business and all other departments will continue to operate at The Tribune's office at 3825 S. Higuera Street with the same San Luis Obispo staff.

All of us at The Tribune thank the press and distribution team for their many years of dedication, commitment and excellence. We will miss you.

Here are photos of the team at work, taken by Tribune photographers Joe Johnston and David Middlecamp.
link_name: A tribute to The Tribune press room

status_message:
With Bishop Peak in the distance, a US Airways flight from Phoenix prepares for landing at the San Luis Obispo County Regional Airport (SBP) on Monday, taking an unusual route by landing toward the southeast. Typically, planes take off and land facing northwest — with nose pointing into the breezes that come off the coast. But strong winds from the southeast have air traffic controllers directing planes into and out of the airport from the opposite direction. Tribune photo by Joe Johnston.

Check out more photos here: http://www.sanluisobispo.com/photos/

status_message: If you've read our story today (http://tribne.ws/11OCh49) you know about Chevron's plans for the future of its tank farm property. But do you know about the property's past? In 1926, a lightning strike ignited a massive fire that shot flames 75 feet in the air and released millions of barrels of flaming crude oil. Read more about it on our Photos from the Vault blog: http://tribne.ws/1bWVWDQ
link_name: Timeline Photos
